{
  "updated_summary": "Tessa Virtue, in a deep red sequined dress, and Scott Moir, in a black lace-patterned top, conclude their PyeongChang 2018 Free Dance routine with an emotional embrace, set to an uplifting, orchestral-electronic instrumental track, prompting cheers from Canadian team members in red and black 'CANADA' apparel as the scoreboard confirms their Free Dance score of 118.10. The team celebrates with hugs and Canadian flags. A flashback shows their Short Program performance at PyeongChang 2018, where Tessa wears a black dress with gold leopard-print accents and Scott a black lace top, executing synchronized movements and lifts on the ice, accompanied by the sounds of ice skates scraping and gliding, and a rhythmic, percussive beat, while the Olympic Channel logo remains visible and a 'SHORT PROGRAM – TEAM COMPETITION PYEONGCHANG 2018' indicator appears. During the Short Program, Tessa and Scott, in matching black costumes with gold leopard-print accents and lace, glide across the PyeongChang 2018 rink, which features purple Olympic-branded boards and Olympic rings, performing complex lifts, spins, and intricate footwork to an upbeat, rhythmic pop/dance track and a dramatic orchestral score. A female commentator remarks on their "different level" of performance and their seamless partnership, noting their "changes of hold and direction" and "extraordinary skating skills," while a male commentator highlights their "rumba" and technical prowess, "using the lean of the edge." The audience watches intently, capturing the moment, as the Canadian score updates from 11.90 to 18.20, then to 44.25, surpassing the USA's 40.33. The commentator anticipates "just the lift to go" as the routine nears its climax, culminating in a close embrace, eliciting a huge crowd roar. The male commentator praises their "impressive" performance, identifying them as "the reigning world champions" in what might be their "last competitive short skate," as they skate hand-in-hand, raising their arms in victory, acknowledging the enthusiastic audience waving Canadian flags and signs, all set to upbeat, electronic instrumental music."
}
